I"R<h1 id="get-ready-to-start-using-and-contributing-to-bitcoin-dev-kit">Get ready to start using and contributing to Bitcoin Dev Kit:</h1>
<p>The purpose of this document is to provide resources and tutorials for individuals would like to use the BDK library. This document has enough resources and tutorials for a beginner, intermediate developers to learn the basics of using BDK through examples. Whether you are looking to contribute, develop, or create your own bitcoin application this guide should cover everything you need to get started.</p>

<p>Purpose:</p>

<p>I created this document for those looking for resources or a guide to start using or contributing to BDK. This is a work in progress but should suffice for anyone looking to start learning today.</p>

<p>What should you expect to get from this guide:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Be exposed to BDK features and library to start contributing, developing, and creating.</li>
  <li>Hands-on tutorials in order to learn by doing.</li>
  <li>Learn through example how you can use BDK into your Bitcoin application or project.</li>
</ul>

<p>Developers:</p>
<ul>
  <li>You will be able to reproduce these steps covered in tutorials to create your own custom Bitcoin wallet or app.</li>
  <li>You can use the main Rust library or use the BDK language-bindings that include Java, Swift, Python.</li>
  <li></li>
</ul>

<p>Lets get started :</p>

<p>Easy:
Beginner Tutorials:</p>
<ul>
  <li>BDK-CLI Basics: Single-Sig Testnet transaction</li>
  <li>BDK-CLI Basics: 2-of-3 Multi-Sig Testnet Transaction</li>
  <li>Mastering Bitcoin Book : Bitcoin Dev Kit and BDK-CLI  ( 3 Wallet Examples)
Intermediate:</li>
  <li>
    <p>BDK-CLI MiniScript Policy Decoded: : 3-of-3 multi-sig or 2-of-3 and relative-timelock</p>
  </li>
  <li>Bitcoin Developers : Learning BDK from the Command line (Youtube Video)</li>
</ul>

